doctype html
html
  head
    script(type="text/javascript", src="/js/how-to-use.js")
    link(rel="stylesheet", type="text/css", href="/css/style.css")
    title AnyFetch chrome extension
  body.how-to-use
    header.row.container
      .col-sm-8.col-sm-offset-2.col-md-6.col-md-offset-3.col-lg-4.col-lg-offset-4
        img.logo(src="/images/icons/anyfetch_icon.svg", alt="AnyFetch Icon")
        | &nbsp;Any
        b Fetch
    .vertical-align
      .row.container
        section.content.col-sm-8.col-sm-offset-2.col-md-6.col-md-offset-3.col-lg-4.col-lg-offset-4
          h1 How to use the extension
          ol.steps
            li
              p As you browse all around the web, the extension will detect the important websites, and try to figure out what you may be looking for.
            li
              p When the extension found something, an icon, the AnyFetch icon, will appear in your navigation bar:
              img.chrome-example(src="/images/chrome-example.png", alt="")
            li
              p
                | The icon will be blue (
                img.page-action-icon(src="/images/icons/extension/page-action/icon38.png", alt="")
                | ) if there is a match in the documents you have indexed in AnyFetch. Just click it to view the search.
              p
                | If the icon is gray (
                img.page-action-icon(src="/images/icons/extension/page-action/icon38_grayscale.png", alt="")
                | ), this means there are no matches in your documents.
            li
              p Here are some examples of supported sites, that you may try right now
              ul
                li A LinkedIn profile
                li A facebook friend
                li An email in Gmail
                li A Google search
          a(href="")#close I'm ready, close this!
